### 7. Calculations

#### Power

\[
P = 1.8 \times 200\mu A = 0.36\text{ mW}
\]

#### Resistor

\[
R_d = \frac{1.8 - 0.9}{200\mu A} = 4.5k\Omega
\]

#### Width Optimization

- \( W = 2.84\mu m \rightarrow 115.2\mu A \)  
- \( W = 5.18\mu m \rightarrow 200.124\mu A \)  

Final:  
\( W = 5.18144\mu m \)

#### Gain (Simulated)

\[
A_v = \frac{63.832}{19.218} = 3.3214 \approx 10.4265\text{ dB}
\]

#### Gain (Theoretical)

\[
g_m = \frac{2I_D}{V_{SG} - |V_t|}
\]

\[
A_v = g_m R_d = 3.529 \approx 10.954\text{ dB}
\]

---

### 8. Result and Inference

- Desired Q-point achieved successfully  
- Power consumption remains within limits  
- Minor gain error (~4.8%) due to channel length modulation  
- Adding 10 pF capacitor reduces bandwidth drastically, confirming dominant pole behavior
